        <title><m>\S VI.4</m>: Newton's Method</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: Newton's Method </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Recall, the Intermediate Value Theorem gave us a method for approximating zeros of functions
                            using bisection, but it was slow! Using derivatives, we can do better.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="8in">
                    <title>Example: Approximating <m>\pi</m></title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            We'd like to approximate a solution to <m>f(x) = \sin(x) = 0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            See notes from class. Using Newton's method (with equations of tangent lines), we get an 
                            approximation of <m>\pi \approx 3.1415926533</m> after just two iterations!
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="6in">
                    <title>Newton's Method</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            To approximate solutions to <m>f(x)=0</m>, we can compute a sequence of approximations by
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Choosing <m>x_0</m> close to <m>x</m>. The Intermediate Value Theorem is often
                                        useful.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        If <m>x_n</m> is your current approximation, then 
                                        <me>
                                            x_{n+1} = \frac{-f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)}+ x_n
                                        </me>.
                                        This comes from finding the zero of the equation of the tangent line to <m>f</m> at <m>x_n</m>.
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="6in">
                    <title>Practice: Newton's Method</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Use Newton's method to approximate solutions to the following with three iterations (that is, compute
                            <m>x_3</m>).
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>f(x) = x^2 - 7=0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>g(x) = e^x - 7=0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        See notes from class. After three iterations, we get <m>x_3 \approx 2.64575205</m>. Compare
                                        this to <m>\sqrt{7}</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        See notes from class. After three iterations, we get <m>x_3 \approx 1.95838719705</m>. Compare
                                        this to <m>\ln{7}</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            

